[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating API Reflection**\n\nI’m thinking about using public API and how reflections should ideally be avoided unless required. Existing tests leverage reflection for classloading, but would dynamic coverage still track it? If I go with a top-level public class, I face challenges since multiple public top-level classes in one file isn’t allowed. Considering using a package-private constructor might help, but utilizing setAccessible for direct reflection could complicate matters. Should I keep the scenario nested or make it public in its own file?\n\n**Considering Class Structure**\n\nI’m contemplating that one-to-one mapping indicates the active class should have its dedicated Java test file. I wonder if using a helper file could violate this principle, so I want to avoid it. An alternative might be to make the scenario a public static inner class of a package-private top-level helper. I’m thinking about using reflection to get the method on this public nested class. Would the package-private outer class affect access? It’s confusing with JVM access and binary flags.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_04bd19842fb743880169fc14e0b3a481a1a0161fa3d035230f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_BTvFa0GOY1mtuY3gaaoiK0Xr8VR96lGTrYKSb7Bc7V-RfE9VLrbXPD5b4WCAe6apOhTua0PqT-3i4uYfm6R2BgOslcZuuVeANHjT8uGX3GARyGKeRl_AXhtzg3HhECOnxWicqmSyRde0mrUZ0wfKWLczv4dfed8kauCS06UH0Y1jjLRnjnnbuhs_KW8CpAHMlR5s93GNNlOPpUStMygFCxqZo24rPL9oFug_oYyg2XvAZ_iyE65ARtjr_t0osEhEL76L6_ArhJTZfKoUwnY-dDIG8Bt5g13DWrvnZCM1kwdxEQxCSoDXjTSY3k0nwM8s3w0kWe79AV0LD8QDxt7r0JDt2T4DBI-sv9cM9SajGqRS4O3U7OQ72UiFwaDMOOkBx0gyrpCuJRAM0nI5qYqAITxuoGjWAE8HUafAaSsuQckCTc7rx-hIsmTY4eJspb5PuB8ZPWxo9KnGbzZxEdCoNmFgPV9PDuIHZT_-r1fELt81dVOGfkVu7y1BUH4S14JIOMKdCWnZBHts-VxWmMg55GGmZCJx8L4iDyIrgQTNa9-LXUqldAVA-wybymT34eWjkekuxnqn_np8-wfcKSS-qRq5UfO3_WPoiCHPqnzjBk8oioh8MTyPEavE8AmF4Ihk2ORfzHjFSAAexJMo9a9